WEBVTT

00:06.381 --> 00:09.551
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

00:14.139 --> 00:16.474
(SOFT INSTRUMENTAL MUSIC PLAYING)

00:33.742 --> 00:35.452
(SCREECHES)

00:35.827 --> 00:37.245
(GROWLS SOFTLY)

00:41.374 --> 00:44.169
(CLOUD RUMBLING)

00:44.294 --> 00:46.421
(JEEP ENGINE WHIRRING)

00:47.422 --> 00:50.800
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

00:52.177 --> 00:54.512
GEORGE: Let's hope we don't see
what the lions do at night.

00:54.637 --> 00:56.014
(WILL LAUGHING)

00:56.139 --> 00:57.891
Let's hope we see lions
before they see us.

00:57.974 --> 00:59.184
(WILL LAUGHING)

00:59.768 --> 01:01.603
Hey, Rem. Can you cut the lights?

01:04.022 --> 01:05.065
Cool.

01:07.192 --> 01:09.069
(CRICKETS CHIRPING)

01:23.541 --> 01:25.752
Well, this is... We got a pair
of night vision goggles,

01:25.877 --> 01:28.171
and if you look out there,
and tell me what you see.

01:29.214 --> 01:32.592
I need night vision goggles
to get the night vision goggles from you.

01:32.675 --> 01:34.344
(BOTH LAUGH)

01:39.599 --> 01:41.893
Well, I can see they're wildebeest.

01:42.811 --> 01:44.104
GEORGE: Well, that's a start.

01:45.897 --> 01:49.150
Can you tell their shape?
Like the shape of the... of the group?

01:50.110 --> 01:51.236
WILL: I can't tell, really...

01:51.319 --> 01:54.155
They're like layered up,
so I can't really tell.

01:54.489 --> 01:56.157
-GEORGE: Kind of stacked up?
-WILL: Yeah.

01:59.744 --> 02:02.330
GEORGE: I don't know. Let's see what...
I've got a... another toy

02:02.413 --> 02:03.748
I wanted to show you.

02:04.374 --> 02:05.750
(BIRDS CHITTERING)

02:05.834 --> 02:07.627
(WILDEBEEST GRUMBLES)

02:09.838 --> 02:11.965
(FOLIAGE RUSTLING)

02:17.720 --> 02:20.098
I wonder if a lion could see
in this kind of darkness. I dunno.

02:20.181 --> 02:22.058
WILL: Well, that's...
We don't need to find out that. (CHUCKLES)

02:22.142 --> 02:24.310
GEORGE: No, no, I just die... I'd...
I'd die with the wildebeest.

02:25.395 --> 02:26.646
-You can follow me?
-WILL: I can't see.

02:26.771 --> 02:29.190
-GEORGE: Yeah, I got you, we're good.
-WILL: All right. Hold on.

02:31.401 --> 02:34.529
WILL:<i> My whole life,</i>
<i>I've wanted to see wildebeest.</i>

02:35.113 --> 02:39.450
I just didn't think it would be
in the dark with lions everywhere.

02:40.243 --> 02:43.496
But George has a different way
of looking at everything.

02:44.873 --> 02:47.000
(CAMERA DRONE WHIRRING)

02:47.083 --> 02:48.960
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

03:01.973 --> 03:05.101
GEORGE: Well, we're looking at these guys,
it's interesting, they're moving out.

03:05.476 --> 03:06.728
WILL: <i>Oh, wow, yeah.</i>

03:09.522 --> 03:11.733
GEORGE: But I don't think
they can see anything at night.

03:11.816 --> 03:15.278
So they're falling in like that,
but they're not falling in based on sight?

03:15.403 --> 03:16.613
GEORGE: That's right.

03:23.244 --> 03:24.621
They're walking differently.

03:24.787 --> 03:27.832
<i>Almost kind of like</i>
<i>a loose defensive formation.</i>

03:31.544 --> 03:33.546
<i>They're coming together</i>
<i>and working as a group.</i>

03:41.471 --> 03:44.641
-They're clearly following each other.
-GEORGE: That's right.

03:45.058 --> 03:48.353
WILL: <i>But if they don't see well,</i>
<i>and they're not making any noise,</i>

03:48.478 --> 03:50.313
<i>how do they know where the others are?</i>

04:05.954 --> 04:10.625
Around thirty years ago, I picked up
a <i>National Geographic Magazine</i>

04:10.708 --> 04:12.168
and saw this.

04:13.962 --> 04:18.883
That image, one and a half million
wildebeests on the plains of Africa,

04:19.008 --> 04:21.219
has stayed with me ever since.

04:24.138 --> 04:28.017
<i>The most dramatic migration on Earth.</i>

04:29.811 --> 04:32.397
<i>And finally, I'm here to see it.</i>

04:32.689 --> 04:34.399
(YAWNS AUDIBLY)

04:37.777 --> 04:39.570
GEORGE: Hey, Will.
Come up and take a look.

04:40.029 --> 04:41.030
WILL: All right.

04:41.239 --> 04:42.657
(GROANING)

04:46.661 --> 04:47.745
Whoa!

04:51.708 --> 04:53.626
GEORGE: That's a lot of wildebeest, man.

04:53.835 --> 04:54.919
(WILDEBEEST BLEATING)

04:55.169 --> 04:59.465
WILL: <i>Seeing them up close, finally.</i>
<i>Man, they're kind of funny-looking.</i>

04:59.590 --> 05:01.259
(CHUCKLES)

05:02.010 --> 05:04.178
GEORGE: <i>Wildebeest</i>
<i>are not the most elegant animal.</i>

05:04.512 --> 05:05.930
<i>Or the most intelligent.</i>

05:08.099 --> 05:10.727
WILL: <i>George is straight-up</i>
<i>clowning wildebeest.</i>

05:14.147 --> 05:17.817
<i>But, hey, if they don't get by</i>
<i>on their looks or their brains,</i>

05:18.067 --> 05:20.236
<i>how do they survive out here in the wild?</i>

05:22.238 --> 05:24.782
<i>Well, that's what George wants me to see.</i>

05:28.369 --> 05:32.415
<i>The front runners chow down on the grass</i>
<i>ahead of the herd,</i>

05:32.623 --> 05:35.668
<i>so they all have</i>
<i>to keep constantly moving.</i>

05:37.253 --> 05:38.379
<i>And so do we.</i>

05:39.464 --> 05:42.300
So, George, what got you to... to Africa?

05:42.759 --> 05:45.303
I got kind of bored, I was a...
kind of bored college student,

05:45.386 --> 05:47.388
and I decided to get the hell out,
and I wanted...

05:47.472 --> 05:49.307
I went to Africa, I came hitchhiking here.

05:49.390 --> 05:50.850
-I bought a one-way ticket to London...
-Wow.

05:50.933 --> 05:53.102
-...and I hitchhiked down to Congo.
-Whoa.

05:53.186 --> 05:55.730
And I found it was really fascinating
and there was so much more to learn.

05:55.813 --> 05:57.523
-WILL: Yeah.
-And I still feel that way.

05:57.648 --> 06:00.193
Once you get into dangerous things,
you just keep on learning more and more.

06:00.276 --> 06:01.569
WILL: Yeah. Exactly.

06:03.196 --> 06:06.616
What kind of image
are you hoping to capture?

06:07.158 --> 06:11.120
Well, I'm trying to capture
the key moment in the migration

06:11.204 --> 06:13.873
when the, um... when the wildebeest
cross the river.

06:14.248 --> 06:17.335
How often do you capture
exactly what you're looking for?

06:17.585 --> 06:20.421
(BOTH LAUGH)

06:20.797 --> 06:22.465
That's kind of a depressing question.

06:22.548 --> 06:23.841
(LAUGHS)

06:25.802 --> 06:28.262
GEORGE:<i> I've been photographing wildlife</i>
<i>for over forty years.</i>

06:29.097 --> 06:33.059
<i>As a photographer, you try to capture</i>
<i>these incisive moments in an animal,</i>

06:33.142 --> 06:35.978
<i>where they reveal the true nature</i>
<i>of their species.</i>

06:36.104 --> 06:39.232
And the greatest, the biggie of all,
is the crossing of the wildebeest.

06:39.440 --> 06:42.151
(BLEATS)

06:43.486 --> 06:46.406
In your experience, Rem, how rare is it?

06:46.489 --> 06:50.118
How easy will it be for you
to catch a crossing?

06:50.535 --> 06:53.538
You have a big chance
of seeing a wildebeest, of course.

06:53.704 --> 06:55.915
-WILL: Yeah.
-But it's seeing crossing,

06:55.998 --> 06:57.500
that's very rare.

06:57.583 --> 06:59.585
But I think you can consider it
a great failure

06:59.669 --> 07:01.838
if you don't show me a... a crossing.

07:01.921 --> 07:03.297
-Of course.
-(LAUGHS)

07:03.381 --> 07:04.882
You know, wildebeest don't care...

07:04.966 --> 07:07.260
wildebeest don't care who you are,
or how long you've been waiting.

07:07.343 --> 07:08.970
-I know, right. (LAUGHS)
-They don't really care.

07:09.095 --> 07:11.222
Hey, you guys, do you know what?
The wildebeest haven't seen

07:11.305 --> 07:14.851
<i>Men in Black,</i> I guess. (CHUCKLES)

07:15.309 --> 07:17.728
(WILDEBEEST BLEATING)

07:18.604 --> 07:22.608
<i>In fairness, they've got</i>
<i>more pressing things to think about.</i>

07:25.736 --> 07:31.200
<i>But somehow, between them,</i>
<i>they manage to survive a 300-mile trek</i>

07:31.325 --> 07:34.412
<i>past hungry lions, hyenas, and cheetahs.</i>

07:35.746 --> 07:37.415
What's their secret?

07:38.249 --> 07:41.919
<i>Perhaps the answer lies</i>
<i>in a completely different creature</i>

07:42.211 --> 07:45.089
<i>over 3,000 miles away from here.</i>

07:47.884 --> 07:50.303
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

07:53.347 --> 07:56.184
(SOFT VOCAL MUSIC PLAYING)

07:56.392 --> 07:57.810
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

08:05.151 --> 08:09.906
(BEES BUZZING)

08:16.204 --> 08:18.873
WILL:
<i>But what can the world's largest honeybee</i>

08:18.956 --> 08:20.875
<i>tell us about wildebeest?</i>

08:22.251 --> 08:24.295
ALDO: <i>Have you seen bees like this before?</i>

08:24.378 --> 08:26.797
CORY: <i>I've never seen</i>
<i>anything like this before.</i>

08:30.760 --> 08:34.931
Your problem's gonna be how
to get in there and be able to then...

08:35.097 --> 08:37.475
-sort yourself out to be able to shoot.
-Not... Okay, yeah.

08:37.558 --> 08:39.519
-So I'm not spinning in space.
-Yeah.

08:40.061 --> 08:42.813
(BEES BUZZING)

08:43.231 --> 08:45.107
ALDO:<i> Maybe we'll try</i>
<i>and climb up from the bottom</i>

08:45.191 --> 08:48.027
<i>and then, from there,</i>
<i>try to get in position.</i>

08:50.029 --> 08:52.907
Well, I guess we should go try it.

08:53.866 --> 08:56.953
(BEES BUZZING)

09:01.082 --> 09:03.793
MALE VOICE:

09:04.126 --> 09:05.753
(SPEAKING NEPALI)

09:08.005 --> 09:10.049
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING)

09:21.519 --> 09:24.522
MALE VOICE 1:

09:31.362 --> 09:36.367
CORY:<i> There can be as many</i>
<i>as 100,000 bees on a single hive.</i>

09:37.493 --> 09:39.287
<i>And they can be pretty damn hostile.</i>

09:50.089 --> 09:53.301
<i>If they decide to swarm</i>
<i>when you're at the top of a rope,</i>

09:53.426 --> 09:55.886
<i>there's literally nothing you can do.</i>

09:56.012 --> 09:58.014
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

10:03.144 --> 10:05.146
(BEES BUZZING)

10:05.938 --> 10:07.523
Aldo, I'm in position!

10:07.607 --> 10:09.025
ALDO: (OVER RADIO)
<i>Can you get quite close? Over.</i>

10:10.067 --> 10:11.110
CORY: I can touch it.

10:11.193 --> 10:14.363
I can touch the outer part with my hand
and the inner part with my foot.

10:17.366 --> 10:18.534
I'm gonna try to trigger 'em.

10:19.744 --> 10:22.413
<i>There's a sort of invisible barrier</i>
<i>around a hive.</i>

10:22.580 --> 10:24.457
<i>It's about 20 inches away.</i>

10:25.291 --> 10:28.836
<i>Cross that line,</i>
<i>and something astonishing happens.</i>

10:32.256 --> 10:33.758
(WHIMSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

10:41.432 --> 10:44.393
Wow. Incredible.

10:46.228 --> 10:48.189
<i>It's a kind of defense strategy.</i>

10:49.190 --> 10:52.360
<i>If the bees spot a predator</i>
<i>breaking through that perimeter,</i>

10:53.110 --> 10:57.281
<i>they flip their bodies,</i>
<i>starting this massive chain reaction.</i>

11:00.284 --> 11:04.872
<i>It's like they're somehow all connected,</i>
<i>and not just by touch,</i>

11:05.122 --> 11:08.250
<i>but like they're thinking</i>
<i>as a single unit.</i>

11:11.379 --> 11:13.798
(BEES BUZZING)

11:18.761 --> 11:22.848
WILL:<i> On its own,</i>
<i>each bee doesn't amount to much.</i>

11:24.183 --> 11:28.521
<i>But as a swarm,</i>
<i>they can create something big enough</i>

11:28.729 --> 11:30.690
<i>or confusing enough...</i>

11:31.816 --> 11:34.443
<i>to deter almost any attacker.</i>

11:38.656 --> 11:40.783
(CAR ENGINE WHIRRING)

11:42.910 --> 11:46.914
<i>So the bees have their shimmer trick</i>
<i>to throw off predators.</i>

11:48.582 --> 11:50.793
<i>But the wildebeest don't have that.</i>

11:51.836 --> 11:52.878
<i>I don't think.</i>

11:54.046 --> 11:56.132
So how do they defend themselves?

11:58.342 --> 12:01.387
Rem, there's a lion over there.
Can we stop for a minute?

12:09.437 --> 12:10.479
Look out on the left.

12:14.567 --> 12:16.527
WILL: Oh, yeah, I see her. I see her.

12:25.870 --> 12:28.539
(WILDEBEEST BLEATING)

12:28.831 --> 12:29.874
GEORGE: And...?

12:36.046 --> 12:38.174
WILL: She's gone again. I lost her.

12:43.220 --> 12:45.389
GEORGE: Let's try changing
our perspective.

12:47.057 --> 12:49.643
(CAMERA DRONE WHIRRING)

12:52.688 --> 12:55.483
GEORGE: <i>I've always loved getting up</i>
<i>and looking at things in a new way.</i>

12:56.525 --> 12:58.778
<i>When I was a kid,</i>
<i>I was a real tree climber,</i>

12:58.861 --> 13:00.154
<i>much to my mother's chagrin.</i>

13:00.529 --> 13:02.615
I loved climbing up
to the tallest branches

13:02.698 --> 13:04.492
to get a view over my back yard.

13:04.742 --> 13:06.994
And now my back yard's
become a lot bigger.

13:17.421 --> 13:18.506
WILL: <i>Any luck?</i>

13:21.133 --> 13:22.134
<i>Can you see her?</i>

13:44.031 --> 13:45.616
<i>Wow!</i>

13:47.701 --> 13:49.370
<i>Like a flash mob.</i>

13:53.165 --> 13:57.044
<i>If it were humans down there,</i>
<i>that would be chaos.</i>

13:57.628 --> 14:01.257
I'd be tripping up
and bangin' off this dude,

14:01.340 --> 14:03.843
and runnin' into that guy over there.

14:03.968 --> 14:08.264
<i>But the herd didn't miss a beat.</i>
<i>Just kept on keepin' on.</i>

14:08.931 --> 14:10.307
<i>It looks difficult.</i>

14:10.641 --> 14:14.353
But it turns out, you just have to follow
three simple rules.

14:15.396 --> 14:18.858
<i>Rules that apply to all sorts of animals</i>
<i>that swarm.</i>

14:27.408 --> 14:31.287
<i>Rule number one,</i>
<i>don't get too far away from your neighbor.</i>

14:35.291 --> 14:36.709
<i>Rule number two,</i>

14:37.626 --> 14:40.379
<i>don't get too close</i>
<i>to your neighbor either.</i>

14:44.592 --> 14:49.179
<i>Rule number three,</i>
<i>if your neighbor turns, you turn.</i>

14:53.559 --> 14:56.770
<i>And that's enough to turn</i>
<i>thousands of individuals</i>

14:56.854 --> 15:00.024
<i>into something beautiful and complex.</i>

15:00.399 --> 15:02.359
(WINGS FLAPPING)

15:05.279 --> 15:08.741
<i>Starlings can fly at 40 miles an hour.</i>

15:08.866 --> 15:14.997
<i>So to keep together in formation,</i>
<i>they need the reactions of racing drivers.</i>

15:15.831 --> 15:20.294
<i>Especially as the other "cars"</i>
<i>aren't just in front or behind,</i>

15:20.586 --> 15:22.630
<i>they're above and below.</i>

15:23.631 --> 15:28.177
<i>It's hard to get how special that is,</i>
<i>until you see it mapped out.</i>

15:53.118 --> 15:58.082
<i>A hundred thousand birds racing around</i>
<i>a constantly changing track</i>

15:58.165 --> 15:59.875
<i>without a single crash.</i>

16:05.923 --> 16:11.720
That's the way the wildebeest roll too,
with simple rules and not overthinking it.

16:15.057 --> 16:20.229
<i>They're not as fast or as pretty,</i>
<i>but as they search for fresh grass,</i>

16:20.354 --> 16:22.898
<i>the wildebeest are just as coordinated.</i>

16:28.862 --> 16:32.491
<i>Things get more complicated</i>
<i>when they reach the Mara River.</i>

16:37.830 --> 16:41.041
<i>Keeping an eye on the guy</i>
<i>next to you isn't much use,</i>

16:41.125 --> 16:46.714
<i>when you're facing strong currents...</i>
<i>and giant crocs.</i>

16:48.799 --> 16:54.513
<i>It's the single most dangerous part</i>
<i>of the whole 300-mile round trip.</i>

17:00.811 --> 17:01.937
(TRUCK ENGINE WHIRRING)

17:02.229 --> 17:03.564
Wait, we can get out here?

17:03.856 --> 17:05.399
GEORGE: It's safe. Yeah, get out.

17:05.566 --> 17:07.943
WILL: I'm gonna let you
get out first. (LAUGHS)

17:08.027 --> 17:09.278
GEORGE: "That looks good, you go first?"

17:09.361 --> 17:12.031
(ALL CHUCKLE)

17:13.741 --> 17:15.034
WILL: What are we looking at?

17:15.117 --> 17:18.454
Uh, basically, this is the main barrier
that the animals have to go over

17:18.662 --> 17:21.415
to get up to the big grasslands
of the Mara,

17:21.498 --> 17:23.709
where the really good vegetation
is for them at this time of year.

17:24.084 --> 17:25.961
So, what... what are all of these marks?

17:26.336 --> 17:29.798
REMTULLA: Uh, those are
the crossing points, so we mark it.

17:30.090 --> 17:31.884
Like, it's along the river,

17:31.967 --> 17:33.343
so whenever they cross,
we just put the mark,

17:33.427 --> 17:36.555
so we know like, crossing number two,
number three, number four.

17:36.889 --> 17:38.515
GEORGE:
They seem to have a few favorite places.

17:38.640 --> 17:44.021
But if they cross at regular spots,
why is it so hard to catch a crossing?

17:44.104 --> 17:45.731
There's no way to know which one
they're going to choose.

17:45.814 --> 17:46.648
Ah, okay.

17:47.191 --> 17:48.609
Conglomeration of thousands of animals,

17:48.734 --> 17:50.736
and they all might have crossed
at a different place the year before,

17:50.819 --> 17:52.071
so they've gotta have
like a group decision,

17:52.154 --> 17:53.197
-like a swarm decision,
-WILL: Wow.

17:53.322 --> 17:54.782
about which way to go.

17:54.865 --> 17:58.285
We can either hold and wait in one spot,
or we can get fidgety and patrol.

17:58.786 --> 18:00.704
If there was a crossing happening,
we can go there,

18:00.788 --> 18:02.456
but by the time we get there,
it might be over,

18:02.539 --> 18:03.749
so it's like, do you...

18:03.874 --> 18:05.959
It's hard to know
whether you chase after crossings

18:06.043 --> 18:07.711
or do you wait for a crossing
to come to you.

18:07.795 --> 18:08.837
Got it.

18:08.921 --> 18:10.964
So, how long will it take for me
to get comfortable

18:11.048 --> 18:14.051
just letting a fly be on my face
without having to swat it?

18:14.343 --> 18:17.346
'Cause you got two flies on your face
and you're just relaxed.

18:17.513 --> 18:18.597
(ALL LAUGH)

18:18.722 --> 18:20.557
-I'm like, man.
-I just get tired of swatting at them.

18:20.641 --> 18:22.351
Oh, yeah? (LAUGHS)

18:22.434 --> 18:24.812
-Bush... Really bush man. Yeah...
-Oh, man...

18:25.562 --> 18:27.481
All right, so are we waiting
or are we chasing?

18:28.190 --> 18:29.817
My instinct is to find
a really good place.

18:29.900 --> 18:32.903
We got a lot of animals over there.
And if we're in wait, they'll come to us.

18:33.195 --> 18:34.363
-WILL: All right.
-Yeah.

18:35.447 --> 18:38.450
(TRUCK ENGINE REVVING)

18:41.036 --> 18:44.206
So we sort of look where
they're moving to, right?

18:44.289 --> 18:46.917
Yeah, they're coming to the river.
And see, the herd is down here.

18:47.126 --> 18:48.127
WILL: <i>Yeah.</i>

18:50.254 --> 18:52.673
<i>-They're moving faster, yeah.</i>
-GEORGE:<i> Trying to run there...</i>

19:02.015 --> 19:03.517
GEORGE: <i>Are these guys about to cross?</i>

19:06.353 --> 19:08.230
<i>I can't believe how lucky</i>
<i>we're about to get.</i>

19:09.982 --> 19:13.402
WILL:<i> Never underestimate the power</i>
<i>of beginner's luck.</i>

19:14.778 --> 19:17.072
<i>I mean, George has been trying</i>
<i>to get this shot for years,</i>

19:17.156 --> 19:19.825
and I'm here two minutes
and it's all happening.

19:20.534 --> 19:21.535
I'm just saying.

19:21.827 --> 19:23.412
(TRUCK ENGINE REVVING)

19:33.505 --> 19:35.340
Go, George. This is your big moment.

19:44.558 --> 19:46.810
(WATER SPLASHING)

19:48.562 --> 19:51.356
(BLEATS)

19:54.860 --> 19:56.069
<i>He's going on his own.</i>

20:00.365 --> 20:01.742
(BLEATS)

20:07.372 --> 20:08.707
<i>Oh, I can't watch this.</i>

20:10.459 --> 20:11.919
-(BLEATS)
-(MUSIC ENDS SHARPLY)

20:12.085 --> 20:13.378
<i>Oh, man.</i>

20:16.924 --> 20:18.926
(WILDEBEEST BLEATING)

20:22.054 --> 20:23.764
<i>Why did they let him go alone?</i>

20:29.102 --> 20:31.730
<i>Looks like there's a fourth swarm rule.</i>

20:33.690 --> 20:36.777
<i>Don't go where there's crocs.</i>

20:38.195 --> 20:40.113
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

20:44.284 --> 20:47.579
<i>If I saw one of my boys</i>
<i>get wacked by a crocodile,</i>

20:47.996 --> 20:50.707
<i>I'd have second thoughts</i>
<i>about crossing that river too.</i>

20:53.210 --> 20:57.798
Looks like the momentum now
is moving away from this point.

20:58.173 --> 21:00.217
Where it was moving
toward this point before,

21:00.300 --> 21:03.345
now it feels like
it's kind of gently drifting away.

21:03.428 --> 21:05.889
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

21:07.599 --> 21:10.936
<i>Clearly, one brave dude</i>
<i>jumping into the water</i>

21:11.019 --> 21:13.480
<i>is not enough to make them all</i>
<i>start crossing.</i>

21:14.398 --> 21:16.358
<i>So, what will it take?</i>

21:18.735 --> 21:21.989
To best explain that,
we need to go underwater.

21:22.531 --> 21:24.950
(WATER LAPPING)

21:40.340 --> 21:42.092
JILL:<i> They are truly amazing.</i>

21:43.010 --> 21:44.678
<i>The first time I ever saw them,</i>

21:44.928 --> 21:47.139
<i>certainly something</i>
<i>that you'll never forget.</i>

21:55.272 --> 21:57.024
(WATER ECHOES)

22:00.193 --> 22:03.488
(TENSE MUSIC PLAYING)

22:24.134 --> 22:26.261
(INDISTINCT RADIO CHATTER)

22:27.596 --> 22:30.182
WILL: <i>Flashlight fish are weird.</i>

22:31.641 --> 22:35.520
<i>They make their cheeks light up like,</i>
<i>"I'm here, follow me!"</i>

22:37.898 --> 22:40.067
<i>But just like that poor wildebeest,</i>

22:40.359 --> 22:44.446
<i>one fish signaling isn't enough</i>
<i>to make the others follow.</i>

22:44.863 --> 22:46.990
<i>Neither is two or three.</i>

22:48.533 --> 22:51.411
<i>But if enough of them flash</i>
<i>at the same time,</i>

22:51.745 --> 22:53.413
<i>in the same direction...</i>

22:54.623 --> 22:56.208
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

22:57.834 --> 22:59.211
<i>...they all go.</i>

23:07.344 --> 23:12.432
<i>It's not about one animal taking the lead.</i>
<i>It's about enough of them doing it.</i>

23:12.516 --> 23:15.435
<i>Then the swarm behavior kicks in strong.</i>

23:22.484 --> 23:24.236
<i>So this is a numbers game.</i>

23:25.320 --> 23:28.490
<i>The place where the wildebeest</i>
<i>are most likely to cross</i>

23:28.615 --> 23:31.952
<i>is the place where</i>
<i>the biggest numbers are gathering.</i>

23:33.537 --> 23:35.372
(PLANE ENGINE WHIRRING)

23:35.831 --> 23:37.624
<i>But how do you find that?</i>

23:38.083 --> 23:44.297
<i>Well, with a plane with the doors off,</i>
<i>and a crazy co-pilot.</i>

23:48.218 --> 23:50.262
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

24:31.761 --> 24:32.762
Here we go.

24:35.015 --> 24:36.266
WILL: Oh, wow.

24:44.649 --> 24:46.109
Come forward, you can see it better.

24:50.739 --> 24:52.616
WILL: That's a huge line.

24:53.533 --> 24:55.619
That's definitely
the most we've ever seen.

25:08.590 --> 25:13.512
That's crazy. It does look like ants,
like how you see ants move.

25:13.595 --> 25:15.263
-Yeah, like army ants.
-Army ants, yeah.

25:15.347 --> 25:16.348
Exactly.

25:20.185 --> 25:22.896
There's a few thousand there at least.
A convoy.

25:26.566 --> 25:28.360
WILL: <i>That one's even bigger.</i>

25:30.654 --> 25:32.989
<i>You can definitely tell</i>
<i>where this bunch is heading.</i>

25:33.657 --> 25:35.158
<i>Straight to the river.</i>

25:36.368 --> 25:38.537
GEORGE: <i>We gotta get there</i>
<i>before they start crossing.</i>

25:39.162 --> 25:40.789
WILL: <i>Roger that. Let's get down there.</i>

25:41.414 --> 25:42.749
(PLANE WHIRRING LOUDLY)

25:42.958 --> 25:44.626
<i>Let the games begin.</i>

25:51.591 --> 25:53.843
(TRUCK ENGINE WHIRRING)

26:03.186 --> 26:04.688
Look at that line, those lines.

26:11.152 --> 26:12.988
WILL: <i>Have we found</i>
<i>our crossing point, Rem?</i>

26:13.071 --> 26:14.197
REMTULLA: <i>Yeah.</i>

26:20.704 --> 26:22.205
So, I think we better hold here.

26:22.414 --> 26:25.750
'Cause if we drive close, may scare them,
they may run away from the river.

26:26.751 --> 26:30.797
So our presence would potentially
keep them from crossing?

26:30.880 --> 26:33.883
True, yeah.
So, we'd better continue to wait.

26:36.219 --> 26:39.264
WILL: <i>So, now we just wait</i>
<i>for someone to call "action"?</i>

26:41.516 --> 26:43.768
Welcome to wildlife photography.
It's a lot of waiting.

26:43.977 --> 26:45.270
(WILL CHUCKLES)

26:47.230 --> 26:49.107
Eh, it's not different than acting either.

26:49.274 --> 26:52.068
-(CHUCKLES)
-You just kinda sit around and wait.

27:05.498 --> 27:08.960
(WILL HUMMING)

27:09.336 --> 27:13.381
-(BIRDS CHIRPING)
-(WILL HUMMING)

27:13.840 --> 27:16.676
GEORGE AND WILL: (SINGING) <i>A-wimoweh,</i>
<i>a-wimoweh</i>

27:16.760 --> 27:18.178
<i>A-wimoweh, a-wimoweh</i>

27:18.595 --> 27:22.057
<i>A-wimoweh, a-wimoweh</i>
<i>A-wimoweh, a-wimoweh</i>

27:22.265 --> 27:26.227
<i>In the jungle, the mighty jungle</i>

27:26.394 --> 27:30.231
<i>The lion sleeps tonight</i>

27:30.523 --> 27:34.444
<i>In the jungle, the mighty jungle</i>

27:34.569 --> 27:38.490
<i>The lion sleeps tonight</i>

27:38.782 --> 27:44.454
<i>Woo-oo-oo-ooo</i>
<i>Ee-e-e-oh-mum-a-weh</i>

27:45.747 --> 27:47.082
I'm out of breath.

